es between versions, so I can't just update the image from 7.17.9 to 8.11.1 while keeping the existing PVCs. I'll need to delete the current StatefulSet and PVCs to start fresh with a new 3-node cluster running 8.11.1.\n\nFor the elastic user password, since the secret doesn't exist yet, I'll generate one and create it myself. The cleanest approach for ES 8.x is to set the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable during bootstrap, which automatically configures the password on startup.\n\nNow I'm planning out the full deployment strategy: generating the necessary certificates and secrets, then creating the StatefulSet with proper configuration for ES 8.11.1. wildcard cert to keep things simple, so I'll use `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` as the primary SAN along with `es-http` and `localhost` to cover all the necessary DNS names and local access patterns.\n\nGenerating the CA and server certificates using openssl... Signing the certificate with the CA and then creating a Kubernetes secret from the certificate files. For the PVC issue, since this is a fresh ES 8.x deployment and the existing PVCs contain data from ES 7.17.9, I'll delete both the StatefulSet and PVCs to start clean rather than attempting a migration. I also need to handle the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable for bootstrapping the elastic superuser in ES 8.x.\n\nMy deployment plan involves generating TLS certificates locally, creating the necessary secrets, deleting the old StatefulSet and PVCs, updating the ConfigMap with ES 8.x settings including TLS configuration, deploying the new StatefulSet with version 8.11.1, and then verifying HTTPS access. For transport layer security between nodes, I'll use the same certificates as the HTTP layer to keep things simple rather than managing separate transport certificates.\n\nBefore I start implementing, I should check what tools I have available for certificate generation, like openssl, since I'll need to create the TLS certs locally first.","signatur