{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011ErK2KKwBQpuHRSwz3kAiH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that es-cluster-0 is trying to resolve `es-cluster-2.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` and `es-cluster-1.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` but those pods don't exist yet (StatefulSet deploys pods sequentially, waiting for each to be ready before creating the next).\n\nSo we have a chicken-and-egg problem:\n1. StatefulSet won't create es-cluster-1 until es-cluster-0 is Ready\n2. es-cluster-0 won't become Ready until the readiness probe passes (cluster health green/yellow)\n3. Cluster health won't reach green/yellow until all 3 initial master nodes are up, or at least a quorum\n\nBut wait—with `cluster.initial_master_nodes` configured for all 3 nodes, ES 8.x should be able to bootstrap with just es-cluster-0 as the sole node. The real problem is my readiness probe is too strict; it's waiting for cluster health to be green/yellow when the cluster hasn't even formed yet since the other nodes don't exist.\n\nActually, ES 8.x should handle this fine with just es-cluster-0 if it's in the initial_master_nodes list. The DNS failures for the other nodes are normal at startup. I need to figure out whether the issue is just expected DNS resolution failures or if ES is actually blocking bootstrap because it's waiting for a quorum of the 3 configured nodes. Let me trace through what happens when the StatefulSet starts—es-cluster-0 comes up but the readiness probe fails immediately.\n\nThe real problem is a deadlock: the readiness probe tries to hit the cluster health endpoint, which fails because the cluster isn't formed yet, so the pod never becomes Ready, which means the StatefulSet won't start es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2. I could fix this by either simplifying the readiness probe to just check if the port is open, or by using `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` so all three pods start simultaneously instead of sequentially. With Parallel mode, they can all attempt to form the cluster at once. But even then, if ES requires a quorum to elect a master, a single pod still can't bootstrap the cluster alone.\n\nLooking at how ES 8.x actually bootstraps with `cluster.initial_master_nodes` set to all three nodes—it needs a quorum to discover each other and form the cluster state. Once that happens, the setting gets ignored. So the real solution is either using Parallel mode to let all three start together, or only listing es-cluster-0 in the initial master nodes setting (though that risks split-brain issues if it was already bootstrapped). The third option is to make the readiness probe less strict.\n\nI'm leaning toward `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` since it's the cleanest approach—all three pods start at once, discover each other, form the cluster together, and the readiness probe passes once they've all joined.\n\nThe catch is that `podManagementPolicy` is immutable on an existing StatefulSet, so I'll need to delete and recreate it. Since the current pod is stuck in a non-ready state anyway, I can delete the StatefulSet with cascading deletion to clean up the pod, then recreate it with Parallel mode and a lighter readiness probe.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1172,"cache_read_input_tokens":45105,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1172},"output_tokens":42,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dba7340a-94eb-4c5f-a0d8-815ed63dc982","uuid":"b8a45103-91ae-4be9-8f7a-35462c71a492","request_id":"req_011CcfemPJ5SANUftVXTTSJs"}
